segments.text: I believe it's April the 10th, and this is tape number three.
Transcriber, when we transcribe these, just continue where we ended off on tape number two.
Dr. Hubert, now try yours.
Okay.
We're here in the cabin and ready to proceed.
As we go back to the early 1960s,
One of the truly revolutionary changes at A&M came as a result of all of the work on what was then called the Century Study.
Do you have any recollection as to where that idea for a major look forward and an internal study, where that came from?
Who proposed that?
Who thought it up?
I don't know.
who originated the concept, the idea of a century study for Texas A&M.
I do know that although it was not inaugurated until early 60s, that some thought was being given to it in the late 50s in 1959 when I came aboard
Because as I indicated earlier, I think my experience on the committee of 75 over at the University of Texas gave me an edge up in being selected for the position that I first occupied.
But who actually said, let's do it at A&M is unknown to me.
Do you remember anything other than optimism about

that uh effort no as it was beginning it was enthusiastically received by all constituents so far as i know haskell i don't think of a i can't remember a single negative voice concerning the the the conduct of the century council study uh
The quality of the people selected for the century Council.
The fact that it was about half and half.
Farmer student non farmer student.
The fact that there were a number of outstanding women.
On the Council.
These things themselves brought a new tone to the effort.
and I think we're helpful in its getting launched.

The University of Texas had just a short time before concluded its Committee of 75 study, and that may have prompted A&M, I don't know, to proceed accordingly as a mechanism for deciding upon its future.
But nonetheless, it was a fantastic experience for all parties, I believe.
It was, I think, fast moving.
It addressed the questions that were relevant to the university.
What kind of university do we expect to have on our centennial anniversary?
What kind of student body do we want to have?
What kind of programs and curricula?
Where should our strengths be?
Questions of that magnitude, and it was well done.
Concurrent with the Century Council study,
was one done by the faculty called the Aspiration Study.
And it too, it in fact was more specific in its content than was the Century Council Study.
The Century Council Study was in some ways pretty highly generalized in its recommendations.
Whereas the aspiration study was far more to the point and more specific.
And I think a blend of the two helped chart the course for the university in the years to come.
How did faculty members like me get selected for the aspirations committee?
Who selected the members, do you know?
Did you deans make recommendations?
I think we did, Haskell, yes.
And I think the Koch building had some choices also, but nominations also came from the deans of the four colleges, schools.
Was there any hint in your recollection of any high-level predetermination of membership or anything?
That is, the board or Mr. Rutter or somebody saying, put this one, this one, this one?
No, I don't recall that.
Some of that may have happened.
I never heard of any.
I don't recall of it.
I don't recall it at all.

those committees met and their work I know that we call the aspirations committee we had what we called working parties to look at specific topics as those committees were doing their work do you remember much apprehension of anybody as to what the

final recommendations might be from the aspirations committee yes sir I can't pinpoint anything there may be there may have been some anxiety again in the Koch building I'm not sure but I I don't remember that among the Dean's there was any
concern.
Among the deans or their equivalent, among the key administrators, do you recall anyone who was more conservative about any change at that time than any of the others?
Yes, yes.
I think agriculture was far more concerned about big changes.
And
and was somewhat lethargic in embracing some of the changes.
Were you one of the more, using the word liberal now as receptive to change, do you think you were seen as one of the more liberal deans at that point?
I think so, Haskell.
In fact, a few years later, when...
The then College of Arts and Sciences was reorganized into a College of Science and a College of Liberal Arts.
There was some concern among key administrators, the top ones,
about the use of the word liberal arts.
Really, really.
And in fact, I was asked if I had considered a College of Humanities as the title.
But the College of Liberal Arts title prevailed and was finally accepted, although there,
there was some skepticism about the word liberal in the liberal arts.
I was asked at a retreat for administrators that was held up near Teague, Texas at some utilities company meeting house.
I was asked, why is it that you people
in the liberal arts are always the ones who raise cane around here.
It was an interesting session.
I introduced my colleagues to the trivium and the quadrivium from
Greek and Roman times when the liberal arts were first expressed in those terms.
And it was intended to be a serious effort on the part of knowledge purveyors

to embrace those basic disciplines which were non-vocational in nature and which in fact would free, thus liberal, would free the individual from having to participate in menial types of jobs and effort, et cetera.
I was much better prepared on that occasion than I am now
to elaborate upon that early development of the liberal arts through the trivium and the quadrivium.
But it was, I think, an eye-opener for some of my colleagues.
And I think they felt better about it after that
effort on my part to explain the essence and nature of the studies which comprise the liberal arts sector.
Now, the work of the Aspirations Committee took more than a year.
It and all of its subunits that we call the working parties.
Were you and your colleagues in the administration aware of some of the
probable recommendations before the aspirations report was finished?
I don't recall that we were, Haskell.
Weren't supposed to be.
I don't recall that we were at all.
When the report was finished and the recommendation for co-education, voluntary core, racial integration and so forth, what were the initial reactions of the people that you recall?
Mixed.
There was still
among the members of the Century Council some true original Aggies who did not support wholeheartedly the move to coeducational and to a voluntary military.
they did not take it easily.
And I'm going to say among this number, there may have been half a dozen out of the 100 who constituted the members of the Century Council.
But they did not indicate that they wanted to present a minority report.
And I think Harold Dunn's leadership in that regard was another key element in the success of the conclusion of the study.
The final report then, who were some of the strongest supporters on campus that you recall to endorse it?
Oh, on campus?
Yes, sir.
I think it was pretty universally accepted and supported, Haskell.
I can't point out any single voices that were strongest in its support.
Those who might have been
slow to accept it, were quiet, as I recall.
Mr. Rutter, as far as you know, his initial reaction?
I think it was favorable, Haskell, yes.
Now, I understand from Wayne Hall that one of the recommendations that bothered Mr. Rutter was leaving the A&M out of the title.
Yes, that would have...
been a great concern to him.
He wanted the A&M brand locked in.
Do you remember any attempt by any board member to contradict or counteract anything?
No.
No, I don't recall at all.
Now, as I look back on that board,
I say to a number of observers that Mr. Rutter was fortunate in that he had a number of people on the board then who had had major management experience.
Yes.
And that that helped them not to be nitpickers and micromanagers.
Yes.
Let's see.
Was the chairman of the board of Tentaco, was he on board by that time?
I think so.
And Sterling Evans.
And Dow Chemical.
Dow Chemical, Boyle.
Vice President.
Boyle.
Al Davies, former CEO of Sears.
Yes.
Dick Goodson, former CEO of Southwestern.
Yes.
Oh, yes.
These are great names, and they were strongly supportive of the council study.
All right.
As the aspirations, I mean, as those recommendations began to take effect, share some experiences you may recall
as to the effects at the working level of women enrolling and of black students being admitted?
It was a period of, at the working level, in the office, at the desk,
keeping the network alive.
It was a rapid pace environment.
Things were happening so rapidly.
Enrollment picked up quickly.
Space was a problem.
Women were delightful.
They added such a great new chemistry to the campus, a great new characteristic.
Do you remember any anecdotes to illustrate that?
No.
No, I don't.
It was just so fine to have them aboard.
I think it helped with the behavior of the student body general.
In the presence of a lady, one tends to be more careful with one's behavior and language and so forth, and I think in that regard it was a great additive to the campus.
That's not to say that before they came there was not an acceptable level of performance in that regard, but they added that element.
I was concerned about getting new curricula going.
I was concerned, and this is without regard to women and minorities.
This was with respect to the essential components of a college of liberal arts.
I was concerned about getting a philosophy department going.
That was my number one ambition, a department of philosophy.
I dearly wanted to see it come about.
I also wanted at another level.
I wanted to get geography out of agriculture.
And that happened.
How did you do that?
Simply mainly by.
Indicating to the front office that it needed to be done.
And I had some at that time Ed.
Duran, a geographer, I think was supportive of the idea.
Smith, as I recall, who had been in geography with Schleselmann many, many years, was supportive of it, and he was an old liner in the College of Agriculture.
So that happened.
Where did you get the resources for philosophy?
Interesting, it came about in this way.
At that time, early 60s and far beyond earlier, the several churches on the periphery of the campus offered courses in the Bible.
The courses were built into the catalog
They were placed in the catalog in such a way that they were non-denominational, thereby exempting their offering from being criticized as denominationalism.
And almost every, I think almost every
sect around the campus had its campus minister who taught a course.
And they taught the course in their building, not on campus.
Now here's the trick they added to make it purely denominational.
In the battalion, each semester before registration, they would run a little block advertisement saying,
I don't know what the tag was for religion.
Was it religion itself?
Or was it humanities?
I don't know.
But we'll say it was religion.
Religion 101, the Old Testament.
Section 21, Father Donahoe.
location in the Catholic Student Union, well, you know, that's, and likewise for each other, each other denomination or sector of the churches around the campus.
And under the Coordinating Board formula system, that earned some student credit hour dollars for Texas A&M.
Yes.

Now then, I learned on one occasion, and I picked this up through the registrar's office, I think I got a tip from, I don't know that it was Lloyd Heaton himself or someone in the registrar's office, that in one of these classes in religion being offered off campus, and I must say I honestly do not recall which
which church it was associated with, there was a prof, a campus minister teaching the course who was very liberal in student comings and goings.
You really didn't have to attend.
And there were some students who would register, I'm told, I was told at the time,
some students who would register for the course and during an entire semester might attend five times.
Then at the end of the course would receive a passing grade of A or B and get credit for it.
I verified this information, then took it to President Rutter
I says, we're open for a lot of serious embarrassment over this situation.
And we need to reclaim these courses in religion and get them taught on campus by people whom we select, whom we exercise some authority over.
And
We need to do it quickly.
He says, you think it's that bad?
I said, yes, sir, I certainly do.
It would just take one newspaper to pick it up from somewhere from the battalion and what we're doing, and it would be so embarrassing.
He said, what shall we do?
I says, we need to create a department of philosophy.
And we did.
He said, OK.
Who are you going to get to run it?
I said, I'll employ someone.
I'll go to the key places and find.
Among the searches that I made for our first department head in philosophy, I went to Yale.
There I met.
I had corresponded with him earlier.
I met John Orr, O-R-R, brilliant young guy, Presbyterian, incidentally, and he had just finished his doctorate in philosophy, and he had also had his, he had been in the

Yale program of I don't know whether they call it a divinity or a seminary or what but He had been through that Excellent program in religion and had his degree there along with his doctorate in philosophy So I thought that would make him more acceptable to the campus ministers having that background I Met with the ministers
told them of our plans and that we were going to bring the Department of Philosophy on board and that when we did, we would discontinue the off-campus offerings.
They accepted it okay.
I think they were aware all the time that it was an unsafe situation.
John Orr came aboard, did a great job as a one-man department.
He was department head and faculty the first year.
Students hearing about it and registering for the courses just became thirsty for it, Haskell, really excited about the language and philosophy.
And next year I think John employed Manuel Davenport.
I think Manuel came from
One of the California schools, I want to say, but he came with excellent credentials.
He was had received.
I think at his institution that which was called the Albert Schweitzer.
Award for teaching.
Made a great impression during the interview and we brought him on board and
excellent for the department all the way through.
So we got the Department of Philosophy started in that fashion.
Let's see.
Then it was time to separate education and psychology.
We did not have on the campus at that time any
practicing experimental psychologist or a clinical psychologist.
That was far, far out of reach for us.
But we needed an experimentalist who could do some basic research and teaching in the field of psychology and ultimately work toward a degree in psychology.
Again, another interesting development.
At that time, Dr. Sidney O.
Brown, professor in the Department of Biology, had a contract with the United States Air Force doing research on goats, tracking physiological changes in goats
after they had been exposed to low doses of radiation out at our nuclear science center, actually built a goat shed out there, pens and goats.
He would expose the animals to low doses of radiation, then would examine them and their carcasses closely.
The results were just from well received by the Air Force.
This is great stuff.
And they came back to Dr. Brown after a couple of years of this research and they asked him, Dr. Brown, will you add another dimension to your research?
And that is, we'd like to know what behavioral changes take place.
Brown says, that's not my field, but
I'll see about adding a staff member to my research team who's an experimental psychologist and see if we can't get into that field.
Brown came to me and said, told me this story that had been asked of him.
And he said, I'd like to, he says, I think I can, I know a connection over at the University of Texas.
where I can go over there and get them to let me have a half-time psychologist to come over here, appropriate intervals, and assist me in research.
I said, have you made any contacts there yet?
No, I have not.
I said, let me make a suggestion.
If your contract will pay for half of a faculty person, I'll pay the other half.
Let's bring him here full time on that basis and have him begin teaching some courses in experimental psychology.
Good.
Brown was receptive to the idea and we did that.
At that time, Dr. Walter Varvel,
was the principal psychologist I felt on campus, and he was in the Department of Educational Psychology teaching counseling courses and doing it admirably.
His degree, however, had been in experimental psychology, as I recall, University of Kansas.
I asked him for his help.
in finding an experimentalist, a young person who could team up with John Orr.
No, not with John Orr, but with Sidney Brown, and do this work.
Of course, he did a natural thing.
He first contacted, I think, the University of Kansas.
They gave him glowing remarks about a young doctorate named Casey.
Ben Casey or Albert Casey?
Albert, one of the two.
He came aboard.
And I often say that, well, not often, but I sometimes say that our psychology department grew out of a goat research experiment.
That's not too well received, but I think it has some basis in fact.
But it's good for a land grant school that it grew out of a goat herd.
Yes.
Another interesting development at this time, Haskell.
And this likewise has to do with program expansion.
And this is the story of the cyclotron.
I'm not sure of the first portion of this, but I have a hunch that one morning at breakfast, somewhere along the line, W.T.
Doc Daugherty, senior fellow with the Welch Foundation in Houston, and a devoted Aggie,
at breakfast with Earl Rudder said, Earl, much of the cutting edge research in chemistry in the years ahead is going to be done with a cyclotron.
We need one.
And with that beginning,
Incidentally, I think President Rudder had great respect and regard for any recommendation that W.T.
Doherty made.
And so President Rudder began his quest for a cyclotron.
Where do you go to learn something about a cyclotron?
Haskell, at that moment, we did not have a single member of our faculty who had ever performed any experiment whatsoever on a cyclotron.
None.
I think I'm kind in saying we were cyclotron illiterate.
President Rutter said, I'll tell you what we'll do.
We'll take a team out to the University of California at Berkeley and visit their cyclotron Livermore Laboratories, see what's going on out there, what a cyclotron looks like, what it does.
Let's get acquainted with a cyclotron.
And so
I was asked to go out there along with Tom Cherry, Fred Benson, a couple of others.
I don't recall who they were.
We visited for a couple of days on the Berkeley campus.
This was early 60s now, and the student
unrest out there was expressing itself every hour.
We walked through student groups every time we crossed the campus.
I went out there, President Rutter asked me also, Frank, I want you to see if you can find out what they're doing in closed circuit television, what they're teaching in television on their campus.
and see if you can get some clues as to how we might get started in that game."
Tom Cherry and I were paired up to do that search.
We visited the cyclotron.
made prearrangements for someone to meet with Tom Cherry and me and give us a guide through their educational television system.
It happened to be Mel Chastain who was assigned to us.
And we toured the campus.
They had only a closed circuit, but it was an effective one.
When we got home, I prepared my report to President Rutter that it was feasible, gave him an estimate on what the cost would be, and I underestimated it, I think.
But nonetheless, he said, fine, got started.
I told him about the Chastain chap.
and that I'd like to bring him to campus if I could.
We brought him to campus, offered him a job, and that's how we got started in educational television.
First as a closed circuit system.
The cyclotron was an interesting development.
Fred Benson initially was
Let's see, what was the title given to a person?
Project coordinator.
That member of the faculty, that member of the university staff, who represented the faculty's point of view about the building.
Was it project coordinator?
I've forgotten what the title was.

Nonetheless, Fred Benson started out in that position, but after he got started and met some people and brought some consultants to the campus, and I met with all of them, mainly because it was Fred's good recommendation that the cyclotron should be more associated with the Department of Physics.
than it should be with the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
Fred learned from a consultant who was an employee of the Livermore Radiation Laboratory that at Berkeley, the laboratory people did not have faculty status.
And he said that was a great bone of contention every day out there.
He said, so when you start out, give your people faculty status somewhere.
And he says, they're all physicists, mainly.
So physics is a natural location for them.
At any rate, I wound up as project coordinator for the cyclotron, if you can imagine that.
But the deal was this.
And I think this developed from Mr. Dougherty.
Mr. Dougherty said, Earl,
The Welch Foundation will give you $1 million.
You've got to try to see if you can get the Atomic Energy Commission to give you a million.
And the university ought to put up a million.
And for $3 million, you ought to get started in the cyclotron business.
That was an underestimate also.
But nonetheless, that's the way it started out.
The university was to build the building and supply the staff.
The Atomic Energy Commission was to provide the cyclotron instrument itself, that huge piece of equipment, and provide funding for the research on a continuing basis.
This was early 63.
as I recall.
Yeah.
And I've got a sneeze coming up if it materializes.
Excuse me.
We had the consultants in

They did the initial development for a proposal and a plan for the cyclotron, but said very quickly, you must tell someone on your faculty right now, preferably as a member of the Department of Physics who has had cyclotron experience, can write a proposal for a cyclotron.
and write the scientific proposals for research to be supported.
So you can take it to the Atomic Energy Commission and get this funding.
The university employed a professor from, who had had experience at Berkeley, by the name of George Aigo, Aigo.
Prior to that time, however, it was necessary to go to the Atomic Energy Commission, Tennessee, at their Oak Ridge location, and negotiate the contract, the final details of the contract.
The three negotiators the university sent up there were Clyde Freeman, distinguished physicist, Donald Simon,
At that time, my assistant, outstanding scientist, and Frank Hubert.
And you know, I've never had a course in physics.
Chemistry, yes.
Physics, no.
But we went to Oak Ridge, Tennessee, the Atomic Energy Headquarters building there, sat down across the table.
Facing us were 13 scientists.
members of the AEC staff.
There were scientists, there were auditors, there were administrators, the complete ensemble.
Well, you know, I've forgotten the name of the fellow who chaired that group.
But he said, well, how shall we get started, Dean Hubert?
I said, well, the first thing I'd like to know.
It was already agreed that we would do the building, and they would provide the instrument.
I said, the first thing I'd like to know is, where does the cyclotron start?
I knew it had to have lots of electrical power and it had to be plugged in somewhere.
I says, does the cyclotron begin at the point where it is plugged in?
I'd like a clear distinction in my mind between the instrument and the building in terms of cost allocation.
Well, that opened it up easily for us to follow that track in terms of
where the cyclotron begins and what it's going to cost and what kind of building it will require and what type of electrical power it will need.
We spent a couple of hours with them, turned out well, came back, they approved

Ultimately the contract George by that time George Igoe had written a scientific proposal for several research projects and It was funded and off off and running Such an experience but nonetheless At that time this was this was 63 remember now Haskell
At that time, I'm told one of the pressing problems on President Kennedy's desk was, where shall the next cyclotron be built?
Hubert Humphrey badly wanted...
